name: 5-chloro-3-hydroxypyridine
Reason: Base compound pyridine has a melting point of about -42°C. Adding functional groups will tend to increase this value. The hydroxyl group (OH) is capable of forming hydrogen bonds, which typically raises the melting point significantly. On benzene derivatives, the addition of an OH group raises the melting point by approximately 80°C due to intermolecular hydrogen bonding. The chlorine atom also increases the melting point due to its significant contribution to molecular weight and electron-withdrawing effect, which enhances the polarity of the molecule. A chlorine substituent on a benzene ring can increase the melting point by about 40°C compared to benzene itself. Considering the combined effects of OH and Cl on the pyridine ring, the estimated increase would be the sum of the influences of both groups.
Prediction: The base pyridine, being a liquid at room temperature, has a melting point of about -42°C. The hydroxyl group could increase the melting point by approximately +80°C, and the chlorine atom by about +40°C. So, the predicted melting point for 5-chloro-3-hydroxypyridine would be -42 + 80 + 40 = 78°C.
